Testing the SMC on the Linear birth-death-sampling model

Aaron A. King

Here, we simulate a genealogy under a linear birth-death-sampling process and compute its likelihood using the phylopomp SMC algorithm. We compare the latter to the exact likelihood as computed using the formula of Stadler (2010).

library(tidyverse)
library(pomp)
library(phylopomp)
stopifnot(packageVersion("phylopomp")>="0.0.11.0")
set.seed(257012390L)
playLBDP(lambda=2,mu=1,psi=1,times=3,n0=1) %>%
  getInfo(prune=TRUE) -> x
x %>% getInfo(compact=TRUE) %>% plot(points=TRUE)

x$tree %>%
  newick2df(time=3) -> dat
dat %>%
  lbdp_pomp(lambda=2,mu=1,psi=1,method="gillespie") -> pogill

dat %>% 
  lbdp_pomp(lambda=2,mu=1,psi=1,method="euler",delta.t=0.001) -> poeuler

expand_grid(
  lambda=c(1.9,2.0,2.1),
  mu=c(0.9,1.0,1.1),
  psi=c(0.9,1.0,1.1),
  n0=1,
  Np=c(1e2,1e3,1e4,1e5,1e6),
  rep=1:10
) -> res

library(foreach)
library(iterators)
library(doParallel)
library(doRNG)
registerDoParallel()
registerDoRNG(558976750)

foreach (
  p=iter(res,"row"),
  .combine=bind_rows,
  .inorder=FALSE
) %dopar% {
  pogill %>%
    pfilter(
      Np=p$Np,
      params=unlist(p)
    ) %>%
    logLik() -> p$loglikGill
  
  pogill %>%
    pfilter(
      Np=p$Np,
      params=unlist(p)
    ) %>%
    logLik() -> p$loglikEuler
  
  dat %>%
    lbdp_exact(lambda=p$lambda,mu=p$mu,psi=p$psi) -> p$exact
  p
} -> res
library(reshape2)

res %>%
  select(-n0, -rep) %>%
  melt(id.vars=c("lambda","mu","psi","Np","exact")) %>%
  group_by(lambda,mu,psi,Np,exact,variable) %>%
  summarise(
    p25=quantile(value,probs=0.025)[[1]],
    p975=quantile(value,probs=0.975)[[1]],
    p50=quantile(value,probs=.5)[[1]]
  ) %>%
  ungroup() -> test

test %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Np, y=p50, group=variable, color=factor(lambda))) +
  geom_point(aes(shape=variable), position=position_dodge(width=0.9))+
  geom_errorbar(aes(x=Np,ymax=p25,ymin=p975,linetype=variable),na.rm=TRUE,position="dodge") +
  geom_hline(aes(color=factor(lambda),yintercept=exact))+
  facet_grid(
    mu~psi,
    labeller=label_bquote(
      rows=mu==.(mu),
      cols=psi==.(psi)
    )
  )+
  labs(
    color=expression(lambda),
    x=expression(N[p]),
    y=expression(log~L)
  )+
  scale_x_log10(
    labels=function(x)aakmisc::scinot(x,simplify=TRUE)
  )+
  theme_bw(base_size=12)

Dots show the results of SMC computations using the indicated number of particles (\(N_p\)). The horizontal lines are the exact values, as computed by Stadler (2010).
